"1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","1348":"1348","1402":"1402","1446":"1446","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1421":"1421","1497":"1497","1429":"1429","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England":"Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Long Melford, Suffolk, England":"Long Melford, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Foremark Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Foremark, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Kentwell Hall, Long Melford, Suffolk, England":"Long Melford, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Francys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Franceis</i>, modern French <i>François</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>, originally ‘Frank’, though later used to denote a Frenchman. The personal name owed much of its popularity during the Middle Ages to the fame of Saint Francis of Assisi (1181–1226), whose baptismal name was actually <i>Giovanni</i> but who was nicknamed <i>Francisco</i> because his father was absent in France at the time of his birth. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Francesco   and Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian   Franc  , and also their derivatives, e.g. Croatian <b>Francišković</b> (see   Francisco   4).","English: ethnic name from the Old French adjective <i>Franceis</i> ‘French’ (see 1 above).","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames, or an adoption of the non-Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferenc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Casimir, Iwan, Zbigniew.","Hungarian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), Slovenian, and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Ferenc</i>, a Hungarian form of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Fraczek","meanings":["Polish (<b>Frączek</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Franciszek</i>, an equivalent of Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ). It is found mainly in Lesser Poland."]},{"name":"Chico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jesus, Pedro, Rafael, Bernardo, Camilo, Cirilo, Juan, Miguel, Ramona, Ruben.","Spanish: from <i>chico</i> ‘small, young’ (of uncertain origin, perhaps from Latin <i>ciccum</i> ‘trifle’), applied as a nickname for a small man, or for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name.","Portuguese: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francisco</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Francesco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Gabriele, Giovanni, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Carlota, Garcia, Romana.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Francesco</i> (from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>), an equivalent of   Francis  ."]},{"name":"Di Cicco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Pasquale, Carlo, Cosmo, Giovanni, Giulio, Giuseppe, Nicola, Attilio, Benedetto, Carmela.","Italian: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Ceccarelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Dino, Angelo, Dante, Quinto, Sesto, Aldo, Americo, Amerigo, Arcangelo, Augusto, Aurelio, Franco, Gino, Guido, Italo, Leoncio, Renato, Roberto, Tino, Tito, Valerio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Ceccarello</i>, a diminutive of <i>Cecco</i>, itself a diminutive <i>Francesco</i>, from Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Di Cioccio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Cosmo, Mario, Cesidio, Dante, Guido, Salvatore, Aldo, Americo, Benito, Biagio, Domenico, Ezio, Flavio, Nunzio, Quintino, Silverio.","Italian: patronymic from a personal name of uncertain derivation,possibly a pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (see   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cillo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Americo, Aniello, Antonio, Carmine, Gianna, Giovanni, Guido, Livio, Rocco, Vito.","Italian: from a shortened pet form of <i>Francesco</i> (equivalent of   Francis  )."]},{"name":"Cisco","meanings":["Italian (Veneto): from the personal name <i>Cisco</i>, a short form of <i>Francesco</i>, Latin <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","American shortened form of the surname   Francisco   (which is in part of German and presumably also of French origin) and thus a variant of   Sisco   and   Sesco  ."]},{"name":"Fran","meanings":["Croatian: from a short form of local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Franciscus</i> (see   Francis  ).","Spanish: probably an altered form of Catalan   Franc  .","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): from a short form of the Spanish personal name   Franco   or   Francisco  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margery Francys was born in 1402, in Suffolk, England as the daughter of Helias Francis and Mrs. Helias Francis. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with William Clopton. She died in 1445, in Long Melford, Suffolk, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1402–1445":"1402–1445","1383–1446":"1383–1446","1421–1450":"1421–1450","1423–1480":"1423–1480","1423–1497":"1423–1497","1425–1470":"1425–1470","1429–Male":"1429–Surnud","1348–1404":"1348–1404","–Female":"Surnud","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","1348":"1348","1402":"1402","1446":"1446","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1421":"1421","1497":"1497","1429":"1429","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England":"Wickhambrook, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Long Melfor